{"key":"processedPost-19825639","value":{"id":19825639,"first":19822457,"last":19826059,"when":1397184192,"utime":"04/11/14 05:43 AM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>SwampEyes said:</strong><br />from my perspective, it seems more logical to use only a small cutting of SFD, rather than an entire disc over the lid.&nbsp; doing it this way allows you to conserve your SFDs and also to include visible access to an injection port without possibly damaging your SFD.</blockquote><br />It doesn't conserve your filter disks at all to cut them.&nbsp; you can't get under the filter to clean what the grain saturated steam leaves behind.&nbsp; When you use the filter disk whole, you can wash and dry it to put away for next use.&nbsp; I have disks that are over a decade old and have been used thousands of times.&nbsp; Filter disks will far outlast the lids they're used with. . . .unless you cut and glue them.<br />It also allows for better gas exchange to have the whole surface of the filter working.&nbsp; You control the amount by regulating the size of the holes you drill in your lids.<br />RR"}}